<Base title="Scholar case studies" compactHeader={true} toc={toc}>
  <p class="ar-title" lang="ar" dir="rtl">تراجم العلماء</p>
  <h2>Scholar case studies</h2>
  <p class="summary">Sourced biographical-and-methodological sketches of four scholars whose names are central to the Salafī movement and to its disagreement with the classical Sunnī mainstream — Ibn Taymiyya, Muḥammad Nāṣir al-Dīn al-Albānī, ʿAbd al-ʿAzīz ibn Bāz, and Muḥammad ibn al-ʿUthaymīn. For each: a biographical snapshot, the scholar's methodology, their influence, the documented critiques from named Sunnī scholars, and a closing note on where the position aligns with — and departs from — the classical Sunnī mainstream.</p>

  <p class="standards">The standard followed here is the same as the rest of the site: every claim is sourced; named critics are real scholars with real works; respect for genuine learning is preserved even where disagreement is total. None of these men is dismissed.</p>

  <h3 id="ibn-taymiyya">Ibn Taymiyya (Taqī al-Dīn Aḥmad ibn ʿAbd al-Ḥalīm) — d. 728 AH / 1328 CE</h3>

  <p><strong>Biography.</strong> Born in Ḥarrān (modern southeastern Turkey, 1263 CE); his family fled the Mongol invasions and settled in Damascus when he was a child. Educated in the Ḥanbalī madhhab and rose to prominence as a polemicist and jurist. Imprisoned multiple times by the Mamlūk authorities in Damascus and Cairo over various rulings — including a controversial fatwa on triple-divorce and his rejection of mainstream tawassul and ziyāra. Died in the Damascus citadel in 728 AH after his ink and writing materials were confiscated.</p>

  <p><strong>Methodology.</strong> A self-conscious return to what he understood as the methodology of the Salaf — affirmation of divine attributes in apparent meaning <em>bilā kayf</em>, rejection of allegorical ta'wīl, restrictive view of permissible tawassul, broad polemical engagement with the philosophers (<em>falāsifa</em>) and the Twelver Shīʿa. His methodological signature is the principle that revealed text and sound reason cannot truly conflict, and where they appear to, the appearance is the result of philosophical or rationalist overreach (the central thesis of <em>Darʾ Taʿāruḍ al-ʿAql wa-l-Naql</em>).</p>

  <p><strong>Major works.</strong> <em>Majmūʿ al-Fatāwā</em> (a 37-volume fatwa collection), <em>Minhāj al-Sunna al-Nabawiyya</em> (a refutation of Twelver Shīʿism), <em>Darʾ Taʿāruḍ al-ʿAql wa-l-Naql</em>, <em>al-ʿAqīda al-Wāsiṭiyya</em>, <em>Qāʿida Jalīla fī al-Tawassul wa-l-Wasīla</em>.</p>

  <p><strong>Influence.</strong> He is the foundational scholarly authority of the modern Salafī movement, inherited through his student Ibn al-Qayyim al-Jawziyya, then reactivated as a primary reference by Muḥammad ibn ʿAbd al-Wahhāb in the 18th century, and again by 20th-century Salafī scholars (Albānī, Ibn Bāz, Ibn al-ʿUthaymīn, and the Saudi religious establishment).</p>

  <p><strong>Documented criticisms.</strong> Imam Taqī al-Dīn al-Subkī (d. 756 AH), a leading Shāfiʿī jurist of his generation, wrote two extended refutations of specific Ibn Taymiyya positions: <em>al-Sayf al-Ṣaqīl fī al-Radd ʿalā Ibn Zafīl</em> and <em>al-Durra al-Muḍiyya fī al-Radd ʿalā Ibn Taymiyya</em>, focused on his ʿaqīdah on direction and his rulings on tawassul/ziyāra. Ibn Ḥajar al-Haytamī (d. 974 AH) extended the same critique in <em>al-Fatāwā al-Ḥadīthiyya</em>. His own student al-Dhahabī (d. 748 AH) — the great Sunnī biographer — wrote a personal letter near the end of Ibn Taymiyya's life, <em>al-Naṣīḥa al-Dhahabiyya</em>, warning him about the harshness of his polemics and the corrosive effect on his readers. Imam Ibn Ḥajar al-ʿAsqalānī (d. 852 AH) summarised the classical Sunnī assessment in <em>al-Durar al-Kāmina</em>: a brilliant scholar of ḥadīth and refutation of falsafa, with specific creedal positions that were neither inherited from earlier authorities nor accepted by mainline Sunnī scholarship.</p>

  <p><strong>Where the position runs into difficulty.</strong> Ibn Taymiyya's specific creedal departures cannot be traced to "the Ḥanbalī mainstream" before him. Imam Ibn Qudāma al-Maqdisī (d. 620 AH) — the foundational Ḥanbalī jurist whose works are canonical in the school — does not affirm direction (<em>jihah</em>) for Allāh in <em>Lumʿat al-Iʿtiqād</em>. Ibn al-Jawzī (d. 597 AH), another major Ḥanbalī, wrote <em>Daf' Shubah al-Tashbīh</em> — explicitly a refutation of the very anthropomorphism-leaning readings later associated with Ibn Taymiyya — from <em>within</em> the Ḥanbalī tradition, a century before his career. The Mamlūk authorities did not imprison Ibn Taymiyya for fidelity to the four madhāhib but for departing from them: his ruling that triple-ṭalāq pronounced in one sitting counts as one was rejected by all four madhāhib including the Ḥanbalī school he formally followed, and was the immediate cause of his final imprisonment in 726 AH. The classical Sunnī assessment of him as a major scholar with specific creedal departures is not the assessment of opponents; it is, in part, the assessment of his own student.</p>

  <h3 id="albani">Muḥammad Nāṣir al-Dīn al-Albānī — d. 1420 AH / 1999 CE</h3>

  <p><strong>Biography.</strong> Born in Shkodër, Albania (1914 CE); his family migrated to Damascus when he was nine. He did not pass through the classical Sunnī education path of formal isnād-based ijāzah-bearing teachers in ḥadīth, and instead developed his expertise through extensive personal reading in the Ẓāhiriyya Library in Damascus. He worked initially as a watch repairman before devoting himself full-time to ḥadīth study. He never held a formal teaching post in any of the major Sunnī institutions; he taught informally and through prolific writing. He was at various times expelled from Syria and from Saudi Arabia, and lived in Amman, Jordan, under restricted conditions until his death in 1999.</p>

  <p><strong>Methodology.</strong> Independent re-grading of the entire ḥadīth corpus — including reports in <em>Ṣaḥīḥ al-Bukhārī</em> and <em>Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim</em> — based on his own assessment of isnād authenticity and matn coherence. His operative principle: any ḥadīth, regardless of where it appears, must meet his independent standard. He rejected the four-madhhab framework as a binding methodology, advocating instead for "the strongest evidence" (<em>arjaḥ al-adilla</em>) on each question, derived directly by the qualified individual from the texts.</p>

  <p><strong>Major works.</strong> <em>Silsilat al-Aḥādīth al-Ṣaḥīḥa</em>, <em>Silsilat al-Aḥādīth al-Ḍaʿīfa wa-l-Mawḍūʿa</em>, <em>Ṣaḥīḥ wa-Ḍaʿīf al-Jāmiʿ al-Ṣaghīr</em>, <em>Tamām al-Minna fī al-Taʿlīq ʿalā Fiqh al-Sunna</em>, <em>Irwāʾ al-Ghalīl fī Takhrīj Aḥādīth Manār al-Sabīl</em>. He also published "abridged" editions of Ṣaḥīḥ al-Bukhārī and Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim that separated the texts he accepted from those he rejected, and split the Four Sunan into <em>ṣaḥīḥ</em> and <em>ḍaʿīf</em> volumes — placing his individual grading judgement structurally above the canonical compilers'.</p>

  <p><strong>Influence.</strong> Among the most cited Salafī ḥadīth authorities of the 20th century, particularly in the post-1980 globalisation of Salafī fiqh. His re-classifications have shaped Salafī fatwa practice on questions ranging from prayer to women's dress to permissible recreation.</p>

  <p><strong>Documented criticisms — methodological.</strong> The classical Sunnī critique of al-Albānī's project rests on a structural observation: ḥadīth grading by an individual without an authoritative ijāzah chain departs from the very science it claims to recover. The Damascene Shāfiʿī scholar Ḥasan ibn ʿAlī al-Saqqāf catalogued specific instances of contradiction across al-Albānī's gradings in <em>Tanāqudāt al-Albānī al-Wāḍiḥa</em> ("the obvious contradictions of al-Albānī") in three volumes, and earlier in <em>al-Qawl al-Mubīn fī Akhṭāʾ al-Albānī</em>. The Egyptian-Saudi-trained ḥadīth scholar Maḥmūd Saʿīd Mamdūḥ documented al-Albānī's downgrading of authentic Muslim aḥādīth in <em>Tanbīh al-Muslim ilā Taʿaddī al-Albānī ʿalā Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim</em>. The Moroccan Mālikī muḥaddith Shaykh ʿAbdullāh al-Ghumārī (d. 1993) wrote multiple critical works. The Lebanese-American scholar G.F. Haddad's <em>Albani &amp; His Friends</em> compiles a 41-item documented catalogue of al-Albānī's specific positions that depart from the four-madhhab consensus. The recurrent point across these refutations is structural: al-Albānī had no authoritative ḥadīth ijāzah in the riwāya chain that runs through the canonical Sunnī compilers, and was nevertheless willing to reverse those compilers' gradings — a methodological move classical Sunnī scholarship considers requires the ijtihādī qualifications al-Albānī did not possess. The structural critique sharpens further when one recalls that the founding mujtahid Imāms themselves — Abū Ḥanīfa, Mālik, al-Shāfiʿī, and Aḥmad — were themselves mujtahids in ḥadīth authentication, reaching independent judgements on authenticity through their own knowledge of narrators rather than by following another scholar's conclusions; as Sh. Nuh Keller establishes in his appendix to Imam al-Nawawī's <em>al-Maqāṣid</em> ("Hadiths That the Mujtahid Imams Lacked"), "a mujtahid does not do this [i.e., consult Bukhārī or Muslim to rate a ḥadīth]. Rather, he reaches an independent judgement as to whether a particular ḥadīth is truly from the Prophet ... through his own knowledge of ḥadīth narrators and the sciences of ḥadīth, and not from taqlīd or 'following the opinion of another ḥadīth scholar'" (<em>al-Maqāṣid</em>, p. 132). An autodidact regrading the canonical compilers, in a methodology that already operates without recourse to the four madhāhib, removes the safeguards that the four-madhhab framework was designed to provide against precisely this kind of individual-judgement failure.</p>

  <p><strong>Documented criticisms — specific fiqh departures.</strong> Al-Albānī's rejection of the four-madhhab framework produced rulings that depart from positions all four madhāhib accepted historically. Selected examples (citations from his own published works and standard Sunnī refutation literature):</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Zakāt on commercial wealth</strong> — al-Albānī held the 2.5% is not due (<em>Tamām al-Minna</em>, pp. 363–368). The Saudi Salafī scholar ʿAbdullāh ibn Jibrīn observed: "I know of no one who broke the consensus on this issue before al-Albānī."</li>
    <li><strong>Women's gold jewellery</strong> — held prohibited (rings, bracelets, chains) in <em>Ādāb al-Zafāf</em>, against the four-madhhab consensus permitting it.</li>
    <li><strong>I'tikāf</strong> — declared invalid except in the three sacred mosques (Mecca, Madīnah, al-Aqṣā) in <em>Qiyām Ramaḍān</em>, against the four-madhhab consensus that i'tikāf is an emphasised collective Sunnah for any masjid in any locality during the last ten days of Ramaḍān.</li>
    <li><strong>Tarāwīḥ</strong> — limited to 11 rakaʿāt and prohibited beyond that, against the practice of ʿUmar ibn al-Khaṭṭāb (whose institution of 20 rakaʿāt is recorded by al-Bayhaqī in <em>al-Sunan al-Kubrā</em> and the <em>Muṣannaf</em> of Ibn Abī Shaybah) and the four-madhhab convention that followed him.</li>
    <li><strong>Menstruating women and the Qurʾān</strong> — held it permissible for them to recite, touch, and carry the Qurʾān (<em>Tamām al-Minna</em>, p. 107), against the four-madhhab consensus.</li>
    <li><strong>Fasting on Saturdays</strong> — absolutely prohibited (multiple recordings), against the four-madhhab convention permitting it when paired with Friday or Sunday. Al-Albānī's own followers acknowledge no earlier scholar held this.</li>
    <li><strong>Make-up of intentionally missed prayers</strong> — held invalid (<em>al-Hāwī li-Fatāwā al-Albānī</em> 1:236, 1:267–273), against the four-madhhab consensus that the obligation persists.</li>
    <li><strong>Lengthening the beard beyond a fistful</strong> — declared <em>ḥarām</em>, against the broad Sunnī tradition treating beard length as a matter of practice rather than a quantified prohibition.</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Documented criticisms — creedal and polemical.</strong> Al-Albānī classified the Ashʿarī, Māturīdī, and Sufi traditions of mainstream Sunnī Islam as outside <em>Ahl al-Sunnah</em>, and in some passages outside Islam altogether. Given that the Ashʿarī and Māturīdī schools have been the creed of the overwhelming majority of Sunnī Muslims for over a millennium across all four madhāhib, this is a sweeping claim with no precedent in the ʿaqīdah literature of any of the four madhāhib's mainline scholars. He suggested that Imam al-Bukhārī himself was a disbeliever for interpreting the divine "Face" as dominion — a reading that puts the most authoritative ḥadīth compiler in classical Sunnī Islam outside the fold on a matter the four madhāhib have accommodated for centuries. He repeatedly called for the demolition of the Green Dome over the Prophet's ﷺ grave in Madīnah and for the Prophet's ﷺ grave to be moved outside the Mosque — proposals that no senior classical scholar in Islamic history advanced. He issued a 1990s fatwa advising Palestinians to leave Palestine to its Israeli occupiers, on the reasoning that Muslims should not live under non-Muslim rule, drawing sharp rebuttals across the Sunnī spectrum including from within the Salafī tendency. He also did not consider Muḥammad ibn ʿAbd al-Wahhāb himself "Salafī enough," remarking in <em>Bayna al-Wahhābiyya wa-l-Salafiyya</em> that the latter "was like a common man when it came to ḥadīth and had no knowledge of sound or weak ḥadīth."</p>

  <p><strong>Where the position runs into difficulty.</strong> The structural problem is the gap between methodological claim and methodological practice. The claim is fidelity to "the Qurʾān and Sunnah upon the understanding of the Salaf." The practice — re-grading the canonical compilers, suspending the four madhāhib, declaring the historical mainstream of Sunnī ʿaqīdah outside the fold, calling for the demolition of the most-visited site in Sunnī devotional life — describes not a recovery of the Salaf's understanding but the construction of a new individual ijtihād presented as their understanding. The Deobandī, Barelvī, traditional Shāfiʿī, and Mālikī establishments all answer the same question — whether ḥadīth grading and madhhab-suspending fiqh can be exercised by an individual outside the inherited isnād chain — with no. Al-Albānī answered yes. The disagreement is not a matter of personalities; it is a matter of what counts as continuity with the Salaf in the first place.</p>

  <h3 id="ibn-baz">ʿAbd al-ʿAzīz ibn Bāz — d. 1420 AH / 1999 CE</h3>

  <p><strong>Biography.</strong> Born in Riyadh (1912 CE) into a religious family. Lost his sight progressively in his youth, becoming totally blind by his early twenties. Educated in the Saudi religious establishment of his era — a small circle of Najdī Wahhābī scholars — and rose through it: judge, then president of the Islamic University of Medina, then head of the Permanent Committee for Iftāʾ, and from 1993 until his death the Grand Mufti of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.</p>

  <p><strong>Methodology.</strong> Strict Salafī Atharī creed in the line of Ibn Taymiyya — affirmation of divine attributes in apparent meaning <em>bilā kayf</em>, rejection of ta'wīl. Ḥanbalī fiqh formally, with willingness to depart from the school when an alternative position appeared to him better-evidenced. Strong views on classical Sunnī devotional practices: rejection of mawlid celebrations as bidʿa, of tawassul through the deceased Prophet ﷺ as a means leading to shirk, of group dhikr in fixed gatherings as bidʿa.</p>

  <p><strong>Major works.</strong> <em>Majmūʿ Fatāwā wa-Maqālāt Mutanawwiʿa</em> (his collected fatwas and articles, in many volumes), and a series of teaching commentaries on classical creedal works.</p>

  <p><strong>Influence.</strong> Through the Saudi state's official religious establishment, ibn Bāz's positions shaped both Saudi domestic religious policy and — through Saudi-funded mosques, scholarships, and translations — global Salafī fiqh and ʿaqīdah for the second half of the 20th century.</p>

  <p><strong>Documented criticisms.</strong> The most-cited public controversy involved his early fatwa upholding the geocentric model of the universe — affirming that the Earth is stationary and the sun moves around it, citing literal readings of Qurʾānic verses about the sun "running its course." The fatwa was later qualified or revised in some accounts; the original position is still cited in critical scholarship as illustrating a pattern of literalist reading exceeding classical Sunnī interpretive practice. His political fatwas drew sharper criticism: the 1991 fatwa permitting non-Muslim military bases on the Arabian Peninsula during the Gulf War — the same peninsula about which the Prophet ﷺ said "expel the polytheists from the Arabian Peninsula" — was attacked from across the Sunnī spectrum, including from within the Salafī tendency. His sustained position that women should not drive vehicles (revised by the Saudi state itself only after his death) was a fatwa whose textual basis classical Sunnī scholars across multiple madhāhib could not reconstruct from any pre-modern uṣūlī foundation. On classical theological grounds, his positions on tawassul, ziyāra, and the Salafī line on the Ashʿarī/Māturīdī schools are critiqued by scholars across South Asia (Deobandī and Barelvī establishments), the Levantine traditional Sunnī networks (al-Saqqāf, the Ghumārī family), and West African Mālikī ʿulamāʾ.</p>

  <p><strong>Where the position runs into difficulty.</strong> The recurring pattern in the documented critiques is the gap between the institutional authority Ibn Bāz exercised — Grand Mufti of the kingdom that hosts the two Holy Cities — and the textual basis of specific rulings he issued. The geocentric fatwa, the Gulf War fatwa, and his rulings on women's mobility each drew their authority from his office and from Saudi state media reach more than from inherited four-madhhab uṣūl. The classical Sunnī critique is not that he was personally insincere — by every account he was pious and learned within his school — but that the rulings of an institutional muftī require an evidentiary discipline that the documented record sometimes shows missing.</p>

  <h3 id="uthaymin">Muḥammad ibn Ṣāliḥ al-ʿUthaymīn — d. 1421 AH / 2001 CE</h3>

  <p><strong>Biography.</strong> Born in ʿUnayza, Saudi Arabia (1925 CE). Studied with Saudi Salafī scholars including ʿAbd al-Raḥmān ibn al-Saʿdī (a major teacher of his generation) and ibn Bāz. Held the position of khaṭīb at the Grand Mosque of ʿUnayza for over five decades; member of the Saudi Council of Senior Scholars; taught generations of Saudi-trained Salafī scholars and lay Muslims. Died in Mecca in 2001.</p>

  <p><strong>Methodology.</strong> Atharī ʿaqīdah in the line of Ibn Taymiyya and Ibn al-Qayyim — affirmation of attributes in apparent meaning <em>bilā kayf</em>, rejection of ta'wīl. Ḥanbalī fiqh formally, with the same willingness as ibn Bāz to depart from the madhhab when an alternative position appeared to him better-evidenced. Notably less politically engaged than ibn Bāz; primarily a teacher, expositor, and answerer of practical questions of fiqh and ʿaqīdah for lay Muslims.</p>

  <p><strong>Major works.</strong> <em>Sharḥ al-ʿAqīda al-Wāsiṭiyya</em> (his commentary on Ibn Taymiyya's foundational creedal text), <em>al-Sharḥ al-Mumtiʿ ʿalā Zād al-Mustaqniʿ</em> (a 10-volume Ḥanbalī fiqh commentary, his major scholarly legacy), <em>Sharḥ Riyāḍ al-Ṣāliḥīn</em>, his collected <em>Fatāwā</em>, and many teaching audio-cassette series later published as books.</p>

  <p><strong>Influence.</strong> One of the most widely-respected teachers within the contemporary Salafī tradition. His written commentaries are used as standard textbooks in Salafī higher religious education globally. His audio teaching circulates extensively in English translation among Western Salafī communities.</p>

  <p><strong>Documented criticisms.</strong> His positions on tawassul through the Prophet ﷺ, on the prohibition of mawlid, and on the status of group dhikr follow the Saudi Salafī establishment line and are critiqued from the same classical Sunnī directions documented above. The Damascene Ḥanbalī scholar Saʿīd Ramaḍān al-Būṭī (d. 2013) — himself trained in the same Ḥanbalī tradition Ibn al-ʿUthaymīn formally followed — wrote extensively on what he saw as the methodological problems with Saudi-school "non-madhhab" Salafī fiqh, including the lines of reasoning Ibn al-ʿUthaymīn employed in <em>al-Lā Madhhabiyya: Akhṭar Bidʿa Tuhaddid al-Sharīʿa al-Islāmiyya</em>. Specific fatwas — Ibn al-ʿUthaymīn's readings on women's modesty norms, on dealings with non-Salafī Sunnī Muslims (Sufis in particular), and on certain modes of Qurʾān recitation in congregation — depart from established Ḥanbalī school positions in measurable ways that traditional Ḥanbalī commentators have flagged.</p>

  <p><strong>Where the position runs into difficulty.</strong> Ibn al-ʿUthaymīn's own claim is to be Ḥanbalī. The four-madhhab assessment is that "Ḥanbalī when convenient, departing-from-Ḥanbalī when an alternative reading is preferred" is not the same thing as the Ḥanbalī madhhab as classically transmitted. Imam Aḥmad ibn Ḥanbal, Ibn Qudāma, al-Mardāwī, al-Buhūtī — the canonical Ḥanbalī scholars whose works define the school — operated under the discipline of the school's <em>uṣūl</em>, not selectively. The claim to be inside a madhhab while operating under a methodology that suspends the madhhab on demand is internally unstable, and is the structural difficulty that al-Būṭī and the wider classical Sunnī establishment have flagged.</p>

  <h3 id="intro">Common ground</h3>

  <p>Each of the four scholars above is recognised by their critics as a serious scholar within their tradition. The classical Sunnī establishment of their respective eras did not declare them outside Islam, did not anathematise them as individuals, and treated their works as worthy of substantive refutation rather than dismissal — a practice the topic pages on this site try to mirror. The disagreements with them are real and specific, anchored in named earlier scholars and named earlier works. Where a critique is advanced on this site, a reader can follow the citation back to its source and assess it themselves.</p>
